There was a problem with including return, break, continue expressions. Previously i had disabled that every execution of return expression was checked (only event returns were) if the parent function was included. But this is important! Now, in the dependency graph i keep a stack of executionContextIds (updated when the interpreter enters or leaves a function), so that i know which dependencies were created in which function context. Then, when processing the encountered return expressions i know the last dependency index, i fetch all other dependencies also created in that context, check if at least was traversed (which means that it had included a code expression), and if it was i traverse the return dependencies starting from the last dependency index, if not, i disregard that mapping.

Before the dependencies related to slice union problems (branch constructs, returns, break, continues, member expressions, call expr, etc) were handled only once, but the problem is that including some of them can reintroduce problems, that is why fixed point iteration is necessary; the number of dependencies added during fixing slice-union problems is counted, and the process stops when no dependencies are added

ForIn fix, before i kept the index of the next property to be iterated, but the problem is what if the current property is deleted in the forIn loop then the next property should not be +1, but the with the same index. I ended by rewriting it to fetch a list of property names at first iteration (new properties added within the loop are ignored, as in real browsers), and then to remove from that list as the property is consumed

Fixed a problem with callbacks. E.g. the return callback value of [].every determines whether the next iteration will be taken, but itself does not influence any value - it is important from the control-flow point of view, but not from the explicit value point of view. So, when noting breakContinueReturn statements i also note if something is a callback return statement. Then when traversing them, a callback return statement is included if there are dependencies from that context included
